===Etymology===
From {{etyl|la|en}} {{term|adiunctus|lang=la}}, perfect passive participle of {{term/t|la|adiungō||join to}}, from {{term|ad|lang=la}} + {{term/t|la|iungō||join}}.

===Pronunciation=== 
* {{IPA|/ˈædʒʌŋkt/|lang=en}}
* {{hyphenation|ad|junct}}

===Noun===
{{en-noun}}

# An [[appendage]]; something [[attach]]ed to something else in a [[subordinate]] [[capacity]].
#* Shakespeare
#*: Learning is but an '''adjunct''' to our self.
# A [[person]] [[associate]]d with another, usually in a subordinate [[position]]; a [[colleague]].
#: {{rfquotek|Wotton}}
# {{context|grammar|lang=en}} A [[dispensable]] [[phrase]] in a [[clause]] or [[sentence]] that [[amplify|amplifies]] its meaning, such as "for a while" in "I typed for a while".
# {{context|rhetoric|lang=en}} [[symploce|Symploce]].
# {{context|dated|metaphysics|lang=en}} A [[quality]] or [[property]] of the body or mind, whether natural or acquired, such as colour in the body or judgement in the mind.
# {{context|music|lang=en}} A [[key]] or [[scale]] closely related to another as [[principal]]; a relative or attendant key.

